resolution": [771, 500]}, "title": "Everytime ", "last_comment_created": 1778936394588, "content": "", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": true, "comments": 0, "score_up": 29, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "text", "uuid": "1ASsUQOXw8", "is_twitter": false, "is_admin": false, "score": 19, "suggested_sort": 0, "post_flair_class": "fchina", "id": 8621828, "raw_content": "One possible strategic explanation is that publicly praising DJT could create political tension around Xi Jinping inside nationalist or hard-line factions within the Chinese Communist Party. In highly centralized political systems, strong leaders often rely on projecting independence and resistance to foreign influence.  Hard-line critics could portray Xi as becoming too accommodating to the United States or too personally aligned with an American rival power.\n\nIt may appear diplomatic and reduce tensions internationally.\nIt can create uncertainty or suspicion among Xi\u2019s more ideological supporters.  Hard-line communists who prioritize anti-American positioning might question whether Xi is being \u201cvalidated\u201d by a geopolitical competitor.  Internal rivals could use the praise to argue Xi is insufficiently confrontational toward the U.S.\n\nLeaders in rival powers have sometimes used compliments strategically  not necessarily as genuine endorsement, but as a way to influence internal political dynamics, shape perceptions, or complicate an opponent\u2019s coalition.", "author": "iamstadter", "created": 1778945019232, "profile_picture": "T57ukINcQeWY", "community": "TheDonald", "ad_tier": 2, "last_comment_author": "E-dantes", "is_video": false, "video_link": "", "is_new_user": false, "domain": "", "is_crosspost": false, "preview": "", "removal_source": "", "link": "", "author_flair_class": "", "is_removed": false, "media": {"resized_resolutions": [], "blurhash": "", "full_resolution": []}, "title": "Hear me out...subtle reasoning why Trump praised Xi so publicly", "last_comment_created": 1778946844850, "content": "<p>One possible strategic explanation is that publicly praising DJT could create political tension around Xi Jinping inside nationalist or hard-line factions within the Chinese Communist Party. In highly centralized political systems, strong leaders often rely on projecting independence and resistance to foreign influence.  Hard-line critics could portray Xi as becoming too accommodating to the United States or too personally aligned with an American rival power.</p>\n<p>It may appear diplomatic and reduce tensions internationally.\nIt can create uncertainty or suspicion among Xi\u2019s more ideological supporters.  Hard-line communists who prioritize anti-American positioning might question whether Xi is being \u201cvalidated\u201d by a geopolitical competitor.  Internal rivals could use the praise to argue Xi is insufficiently confrontational toward the U.S.</p>\n<p>Leaders in rival powers have sometimes used compliments strategically  not necessarily as genuine endorsement, but as a way to influence internal political dynamics, shape perceptions, or complicate an opponent\u2019s coalition.</p>\n", "score_down": 0, "author_flair_text": "", "pro_tier": 0, "is_stickied": false, "is_nsfw": false, "is_deleted": false, "is_image": false, "comments": 5, "score_up": 19, "is_edited": false, "is_moderator": false, "awards": 0, "vote_state": 2, "link_metadata": {"status": 200}, "post_flair_text": "\ud83d\udd95\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0FUCK\u00a0\u00a0CHINA\u00a0\u00a0\u00a0\ud83d\udd95", "archive_id": ""}, {"is_locked": false, "tweet_id": "2055444109888795049", "sticky_comment": 0, "is_video_mp4": false, "type": "link", "uuid": "1ASsUPG9cA", "is_twitter": true